Time Limit: 1 sec
Memory: 256 MB

Description

In the AZ Nurture classroom, Malay sir recently noticed something suspicious…

Students mark their attendance on a paper sheet, and somehow the number of present students is always a bit too high. Clearly, some proxy attendance is happening. 👀

So one day, Malay sir decided to investigate.

At the classroom gate, a system recorded entry tokens of students as they walked in.

These tokens were stored in an array A of length N (tokens may repeat because multiple students can have the same token type).

Later, Malay sir looked at the attendance sheet, which contained another sequence of tokens B of length M.

Malay sir said:

"If the attendance sheet is honest, the sequence B must appear in the same order as in the entry record A.

The tokens do not need to be consecutive, but their relative order must remain the same."

Your task is to determine whether B can be obtained from A by deleting some elements without changing the order.

If yes, the attendance sheet might be genuine.

Otherwise… Someone definitely tried a proxy today.

Input Format

The first line contains T, the number of test cases.

For each test case:

* The first line contains two space-separated integers N and M, the sizes of arrays A and B respectively.
* The second line contains N space-separated integers, each denoting an element of array A.
* The third line contains M space-separated integers, each denoting an element of array B.

Output Format

Print "YES" (without quotes) if B is a subsequence of A; otherwise, print "NO" (without quotes).

Constraints

1 ≤ T ≤ 10

1 ≤ N, M ≤ 10^4

1 ≤ Ai ≤ 10^9

1 ≤ Bi ≤ 10^9

Sample Input 1
1
3 2
1 4 7
1 7

Sample Output 1
YES

Sample Input 2
1
3 3
21 8 40
21 8 40

Sample Output 2
YES

Sample Input 3
2
3 2
1 4 7
1 7
7 4
1 8 4 7 5 2 7
4 5 7 2

Sample Output 3
YES
NO

Note

In Sample Input 1:

A = [1, 4, 7]
B = [1, 7]

By removing the element 4 from A, we get [1, 7], which is exactly B.

Thus, B is a subsequence of A, so the output is "YES".

In Sample Input 2:

A = [21, 8, 40]
B = [21, 8, 40]

Since B is identical to A, it is obviously a subsequence of A.

Therefore, the output is "YES".

In the second test case of Sample Input 3:

A = [1, 8, 4, 7, 5, 2, 7]
B = [4, 5, 7, 2]

Although all elements of B appear in A, they do not appear in the same relative order required to form a subsequence.

Therefore, B is not a subsequence of A, and the output is "NO".



#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
typedef long long ll;
#define endl "\n"

void solve() {
    int n, m;
    cin >> n >> m;

    vector<int> a(n);
    vector<int> b(m);

    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) cin >> a[i];
    for(int i = 0; i < m; i++) cin >> b[i];

    int i = 0;
    int j = 0;

    while(i < n && j < m)
    {
        if(b[j] == a[i])
        {
            j++;
        }
        i++;
    }
    if(j == m)
    {
        cout<<"YES"<<endl;
    }
    else
    {
        cout<<"NO"<<endl;
    }


}

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int t;
    cin >> t;
    while(t--)
    {
        solve();
    }

    return 0;
}
